"Allied industries" shall refer to such industries as the coal and coke and the refractory industries, the principal manufactured products of which are consumed or used by the metals industries in processing of metallic raw materials into finished or semi-finished products;

"Center" shall mean the Metals Industry Research and Development Center;

"Private sector" shall mean those private entities or individual engaged in metals and allied industries as herein defined;

"Board shall refer to the Board of Trustees of the Metals Industry Research and Development Center.

To render consultation services in the preparation of feasibility studies for new projects for the metals industry;

To provide a periodic analysis of the economic status of the industry and its component sectors as a guide for policy determination by the government and as an individual framework for financial institutions;

To serve as liaison between the private sector and the government agencies implementing industrial policies to provide close rapport required for the successful development of the metals and allied industries; and

To provide computer services, including: the preparation of computer programs for operations research type of applications to the metals industry.

Training, Information Exchange and Accreditation Service;

To operate an information exchange center to gather and disseminate information on recent economic and technological developments, both local and foreign, that are of interest to the industry;

To assemble and maintain an up-to-date library on metals economics and technology;

To collect information and statistics for preparation of comprehensive and up-to-date industry studies;

To collect information and statistics for preparation of comprehensive and up-to-date industry studies;

To maintain, in consultation with the Department of Education and with appropriate existing government agencies and training institutions an effective training program for engineers, technicians and craftsmen to cope with the manpower requirements of metal plants and metal fabrication industries ;

To correlate studies on the various sectors of the metals and allied industries a basis for formulating a development program and a framework for investment to induce the rapid and systematic growth of the industry;

To design, develop, and implement a system of accreditation for skilled laborers, technicians and engineers who have attained a degree of experience or proficiency in the various fields of specialization in the metals and allied industries.

Control and Testing of Metal Products:

To determine and recommend appropriate standards for the metals and allied industries to protect consumers and end-users and to enable local producers to attain quality that will meet international standards;

To study, recommend and provide upon request suitable production methods that private industry may adopt to improve quality and to standardize products to comply with the close tolerance requirements of mass production and modern engineering products;

To provide umpire services in arbitration cases between suppliers and customers dealing with metals or intermediate and finished products of the metals and allied industries;

Metals Research and Development:

To establish a metals research and development laboratory to provide answers to problems encountered by the metals and allied industries;

To provide working experience and opportunities for professional development to creative Filipino engineers at both the professional and student levels in the fields of metals technology;

To develop and introduce methods and processes for the utilization of indigenous raw materials in the manufacture of metal products;

To encourage the development of tributary industries with emphasis on those which may use locally available materials, such as coal chemicals;

To encourage the development of tributary industries with emphasis on those which may use locally available materials, such as coal chemicals;

To undertake fully or lend support to engineering firms which lack physical facilities for performing developmental or evaluation tests in improving existing plant methods or introducing new ones;

To provide technological services to and train manpower in metalcraft industries in the rural areas to improve their production techniques and the quality of their products;

To engage in the manufacture and disposition of metal products which the private sector is in capable or unwilling to manufacture; and

To undertake such other services as may be necessary to carry out the purposes of this Act.

Plan, program, direct, supervise and coordinate all activities of the Center;

Assist the Board in the determination, formulation and implementation of policies, procedures, rules and regulations as may be necessary for the effective operation of the Center;

Promote and maintain close coordination between the government and the private sector engaged in the development and expansion of the metals and allied industries;

Subject to such conditions as the Board may prescribe, to sign personally or through his duly authorized representative, checks, vouchers or other documents involving the acquisition or disposition of property or funds ;and

Perform such other related duties as pertain to the office of an Executive Director and those that may be assigned to him by the Board.

SEC 6. Section Six of Republic Act Numbered Forty Seven Hundred Twenty-Four is hereby amended to read as follows:

"SEC. 6.

Powers and Duties of the Board.

âThe Board of Trustees, in addition to its general corporate powers, shall exercise the following powers and duties:

âThe Board of Trustees, in addition to its general corporate powers, shall exercise the following powers and duties:

To formulate plans and programs and promulgate such policies, procedures, rules and regulations as may be necessary for the effective operation of the Center;

To receive, administer, dispose of and disburse the funds of the Center;

To receive grants, legacies, devises, and donations of whatever kind to the Center. Such grants, legacies, devises and donations shall be tax-exempt and deductible from the income tax return of the giver or his estate as the case may be, upon certification of the Board that said grants, legacies, devises and donations are dedicated to the purposes of the Center;

To appoint and in proper cases take disciplinary action against the technical and administrative personnel of the Center and fix their compensation, terms of office and other conditions of employment:

Provided,

That all positions in the Center shall be exempt from the regulations of the Wage and Position Classification Office:

Provided,

Further,

That all positions in the Center shall be exempt from the regulations of the Wage and Position Classification Office:

Provided,

Further,

That such positions as the Board may declare to be highly technical shall not be subject to the provisions of the civil service law and rules;

To create donor positions which shall accommodate exceptionally qualified engineers or scientists in metallurgy and allied fields from both government and private sector and visiting research scientists;

To enter into contracts for and in behalf of the Center;

Subject to the provisions of Section 7 hereof to allocate and fix the amount of contributions from the private sector as the public interest may require and as the financial condition of the private sector may permit; and

To exercise such other powers and functions as may be necessary to carry out the provisions of this Act.
